## Working with data aka the "laboratory stage".
- https://nbdev.fast.ai/ for exploratory and literate programming (why this matters: https://youtu.be/rX1yGxJijsI : notebooks allow you to annotate your code, notebooks allow you to explore data)
- nbdev combines generating documentation as well as exporting actual python packages on the fly. No need to write extra documentation or copy pasting it into another repo for a packable format. allows for importing the self written modules in other notebooks. 
- has a bit of a learning curve and is heavily opinionated.

## Data pipeline
- https://dlthub.com/docs/dlt-ecosystem/verified-sources/rest_api/basic for ingesting data in an easy to manage format from external apis to several other data sources. benefit here is also that dlt adds metadata that becomes in handy when doing real world data task (incremental update, override, or timestamping updates), it also creates tables with nested information automatically. so you inherit some best practices from enterprise scale data science requirements.
- https://vector.dev/docs/about/under-the-hood/architecture/pipeline-model/ for high performance data processing of stable pipelines (rust, needs to run on your hardware/vps with root access). suitable for in memory processing of streaming data using tcp, udp, or potentially grpc (if you attended Oz's lessons, you know why this might be handy).
